content.problemStatement:
- In C, when you pass variables to a function, the value of the variable is copied and sent to the function.
- This means the function works with its own copy of the data, so any changes made to the parameter inside the function do not affect the original variable in the calling code.

---
**Example:**
```c
#include

// Function to add 10 to num (local copy)
void addTen(int num) {
    num = num + 10;  // Changes only local copy
    printf("Inside function, num = %d\n", num);
}

int main() {
    int number = 5;
    printf("Before function call, number = %d\n", number);

    addTen(number);  // Pass 'number' by value to function

    printf("After function call, number = %d\n", number);
    return 0;
}
```
**Expected Output:**
```default
Before function call, number = 5
Inside function, num = 15
After function call, number = 5
```

